<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Insect Netting Height for Raised Bed Tunnels</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Netting that is too low restricts growth, and netting that is too high becomes harder to manage and secure.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most raised bed tunnels, the best insect netting height is just tall enough to clear the mature crop while maintaining good airflow and easy edge sealing.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Insect netting works best when it creates a complete barrier around the crop. Height plays a major role in how well that barrier holds up over time.
  </p>
  <p>
    Choosing the right height helps balance plant growth, airflow, and ease of use.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Height Works Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> slightly above mature plant height.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for airflow:</strong> enough clearance to prevent crowding.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for pest control:</strong> low enough to seal edges tightly.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The goal is clearance without excess space.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Netting Height Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Height affects how plants grow inside the tunnel and how well the netting can be secured. If the netting is too low, plants press against it and create gaps. If it is too high, it becomes harder to maintain a tight seal.
  </p>

  <p>
    Both situations reduce effectiveness over time.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Best Height by Crop Type</h2>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Crop Type</th>
          <th>Recommended Height</th>
          <th>Why</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Low crops (carrots, lettuce)</strong></td>
          <td>Low tunnel height</td>
          <td>Minimal clearance needed</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Medium crops (brassicas)</strong></td>
          <td>Moderate tunnel height</td>
          <td>Allows for leaf expansion</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Taller crops (peppers, some greens)</strong></td>
          <td>Higher tunnel height</td>
          <td>Prevents crowding and contact</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    Matching tunnel height to crop growth is the simplest way to avoid problems.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Low vs High Tunnels</h2>

  <h3>Lower Tunnels</h3>
  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>easier to secure edges</li>
    <li>better pest exclusion</li>
    <li>less material movement in wind</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Higher Tunnels</h3>
  <ul class="plainList">
    <li>more room for plant growth</li>
    <li>better airflow</li>
    <li>easier access for maintenance</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Most setups fall somewhere in between.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How Height Affects Airflow and Temperature</h2>

  <p>
    Taller tunnels allow more air movement, which helps regulate temperature and humidity. Shorter tunnels hold heat more easily but may limit airflow.
  </p>

  <p>
    The right balance depends on climate and crop sensitivity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Setting Tunnels Too Low</h3>
  <p>
    Plants push against the netting, creating openings for pests.
  </p>

  <h3>Making Tunnels Too Tall</h3>
  <p>
    Harder to seal and more likely to shift in wind.
  </p>

  <h3>Ignoring Growth Over Time</h3>
  <p>
    Tunnels that work early may not work later as plants expand.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Set the Right Height</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Estimate mature plant height.</li>
    <li>Add clearance for airflow and growth.</li>
    <li>Choose hoop height that matches that range.</li>
    <li>Ensure edges can still be sealed tightly.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    Planning for full growth prevents mid-season adjustments.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How This Fits Into Your Tunnel Setup</h2>

  <p>
    Height works together with mesh size, material choice, and edge sealing. A balanced setup provides both effective pest control and healthy plant growth.
  </p>

